# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: post-quantum-cryptography
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In 2024 NIST announced the Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Standard for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] She then showed a cryptographic hash function whose security is equivalent to the computational hardness of SIS.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In 1998, Jeffrey Hoffstein, Jill Pipher, and Joseph H.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Silverman introduced a lattice-based public-key encryption scheme, known as NTRU.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] However, their scheme is not known to be at least as hard as solving a worst-case lattice problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] The first lattice-based public-key encryption scheme whose security was proven under worst-case hardness assumptions was introduced by Oded Regev in 2005, together with the learning with errors problem (LWE).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Since then, much follow-up work has focused on improving Regev's security proof and improving the efficiency of the original scheme.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Much more work has been devoted to constructing additional cryptographic primitives based on LWE and related problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] For example, in 2009, Craig Gentry introduced the first fully homomorphic encryption scheme, which was based on a lattice problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In linear algebra, a lattice $L\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is the set of all integer linear combinations of vectors from a basis $\{\mathbf {b} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {b} _{n}\}$ of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In other words, $L={\Big \{}\sum a_{i}\mathbf {b} _{i}:a_{i}\in \mathbb {Z} {\Big \}}.$ For example, $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ is a lattice, generated by the standard basis for $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Crucially, the basis for a lattice is not unique.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] The most important lattice-based computational problem is the shortest vector problem (SVP or sometimes GapSVP), which asks for an approximate minimal Euclidean length of a non-zero lattice vector.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] This problem is thought to be hard to solve efficiently, even with approximation factors that are polynomial in n , and even with a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Many (though not all) lattice-based cryptographic constructions are known to be secure if SVP is in fact hard in this regime.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] This section presents selected lattice-based schemes, grouped by primitive.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] This section lists a selection of lattice-based schemes for the purpose of digital signatures.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] CRYSTALS-Dilithium or simply Dilithium is built upon module-LWE and module-SIS.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Dilithium was selected by the NIST as the basis for a digital signature standard.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] According to a message from Ray Perlner, writing on behalf of the NIST PQC team, the NIST module-LWE signing standard is to be based on version 3.1 of the Dilithium specification.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] NIST's changes on Dilithium 3.1 intend to support additional randomness in signing (hedged signing) and other improvements.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Dilithium was one of the two digital signature schemes initially chosen by the NIST in their post-quantum cryptography process, the other one being SPHINCS+, which is not based on lattices but on hashes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In August 2023, NIST published FIPS 204 (Initial Public Draft), and started calling Dilithium "Module-Lattice-Based Digital Signature Algorithm" (ML-DSA).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] As of October 2023, ML-DSA was being implemented as a part of Libgcrypt, according to Falko Strenzke.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] In August 2024, NIST officially standardized CRYSTALS-Dilithium under the name ML-DSA, establishing it as the primary standard (FIPS 204) for quantum-resistant digital signatures.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Lattice-based cryptographic constructions hold a great promise for public-key post-quantum cryptography.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Indeed, the main alternative forms of public-key cryptography are schemes based on the hardness of factoring and related problems and schemes based on the hardness of the discrete logarithm and related problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] However, both factoring and the discrete logarithm problem are known to be solvable in polynomial time on a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Furthermore, algorithms for factorization tend to yield algorithms for discrete logarithm, and conversely.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] This further motivates the study of constructions based on alternative assumptions, such as the hardness of lattice problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Many lattice-based cryptographic schemes are known to be secure assuming the *worst-case* hardness of certain lattice problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] I.e., if there exists an algorithm that can efficiently break the cryptographic scheme with non-negligible probability, then there exists an efficient algorithm that solves a certain lattice problem on any input.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] However, for the practical lattice-based constructions (such as schemes based on NTRU and even schemes based on LWE with efficient parameters), meaningful reduction-based guarantees of security are not known.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] Some authors who have investigated concrete security for lattice-based cryptosystems have found that the provable security results for such systems do not provide any meaningful concrete security for practical values of the parameters.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] For many cryptographic primitives, the only known constructions are based on lattices or closely related objects.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/lattice-based-cryptography] These primitives include fully homomorphic encryption, indistinguishability obfuscation, cryptographic multilinear maps, and functional encryption.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] On August 13, 2024, NIST released final versions of the first three Post Quantum Crypto Standards: FIPS 203, FIPS 204, and FIPS 205.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] Academic research on the potential impact of quantum computing dates back to at least 2001.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] A NIST published report from April 2016 cites experts that acknowledge the possibility of quantum technology to render the commonly used RSA algorithm insecure by 2030.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] As a result, a need to standardize quantum-secure cryptographic primitives was pursued.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] Since most symmetric primitives are relatively easy to modify in a way that makes them quantum resistant, efforts have focused on public-key cryptography, namely digital signatures and key encapsulation mechanisms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] In December 2016 NIST initiated a standardization process by announcing a call for proposals.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] Candidates moving on to the second round were announced on January 30, 2019.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] On July 22, 2020, NIST announced seven finalists ("first track"), as well as eight alternate algorithms ("second track").
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] The first track contains the algorithms which appear to have the most promise, and will be considered for standardization at the end of the third round.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] Algorithms in the second track could still become part of the standard, after the third round ends.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] NIST expects some of the alternate candidates to be considered in a fourth round.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] NIST also suggests it may re-open the signature category for new schemes proposals in the future.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] On June 7–9, 2021, NIST conducted the third PQC standardization conference, virtually.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] The conference included candidates' updates and discussions on implementations, on performances, and on security issues of the candidates.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] A small amount of focus was spent on intellectual property concerns.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] After NIST's announcement regarding the finalists and the alternate candidates, various intellectual property concerns were voiced, notably surrounding lattice-based schemes such as Kyber and NewHope.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] NIST holds signed statements from submitting groups clearing any legal claims, but there is still a concern that third parties could raise claims.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] NIST claims that they will take such considerations into account while picking the winning algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] During this round, some candidates have shown to be vulnerable to some attack vectors.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] may change the nested hashes used in their proposals in order for their security claims to hold.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] side channel attack using electromagnetic measurements to extract the secret signing keys.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] A masking may be added in order to resist the attack.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] This adaptation affects performance and should be considered whilst standardizing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] On July 5, 2022, NIST announced the first group of winners from its six-year competition.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] On July 5, 2022, NIST announced four candidates for PQC Standardization Round 4.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] On March 11, 2025, NIST announced the selection of a backup algorithm for KEM.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] On August 13, 2024, NIST released final versions of its first three Post Quantum Crypto Standards.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] On March 11, 2025 NIST released Hamming Quasi-Cyclic (HQC) as the fifth algorithm for post-quantum asymmetric encryption as used for key encapsulation / exchange.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] The new algorithm is as a backup for ML-KEM, the main algorithm for general encryption.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] HQC is a code-based scheme using different math than ML-KEM, thus mitigating possible weaknesses should any be found in the lattice-based ML-KEM.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] The draft standard incorporating the HQC algorithm is expected in early 2026 with the final in 2027.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] NIST received 50 submissions and deemed 40 to be complete and proper according to the submission requirements.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] NIST deemed 14 submissions to pass to the second round.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/nist-post-quantum-cryptography-standardization] NIST has indicated that at least the multivariate candidates will probably require a further round of evaluation.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Mosca's theorem provides the risk analysis framework that helps organizations identify how quickly they need to start migrating.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Their work has gained attention from academics and industry through the PQCrypto conference series hosted since 2006, several workshops on Quantum Safe Cryptography hosted by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI), and the Institute for Quantum Computing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The rumoured existence of widespread harvest now, decrypt later programs has also been seen as a motivation for the early introduction of post-quantum algorithms, as data recorded now may still remain sensitive many years into the future.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In contrast to the threat quantum computing poses to current public-key algorithms, most current symmetric cryptographic algorithms and hash functions are considered to be relatively secure against attacks by quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] While the quantum Grover's algorithm does speed up attacks against symmetric ciphers, doubling the key size can effectively counteract these attacks.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Thus post-quantum symmetric cryptography does not need to differ significantly from current symmetric cryptography.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) released final versions of its first three Post-Quantum Cryptography Standards.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The transition from classical public-key cryptography to post-quantum cryptography (PQC) is considered a long-term, multi-phase process due to the widespread deployment of cryptographic infrastructure across digital systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Migration planning is influenced by factors such as data longevity requirements, regulatory guidance, interoperability constraints, and the operational complexity of replacing embedded cryptographic components.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] One commonly cited risk model is Mosca’s theorem, which estimates the urgency of migration by comparing three time horizons: the time required to transition systems (X), the time during which data must remain secure (Y), and the estimated arrival of cryptographically relevant quantum computers (Z).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] If X + Y > Z, migration is considered urgent.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A major concern motivating early transition is the “harvest now, decrypt later” threat model, in which encrypted data is intercepted and stored with the intention of decrypting it once large-scale quantum computers become available.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Migration strategies frequently emphasize crypto-agility, the capability of systems to rapidly replace cryptographic primitives without major architectural changes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Hybrid cryptographic deployments where classical and post-quantum algorithms are used simultaneously have been tested in protocols such as Transport Layer Security (TLS) to reduce transitional risk.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2024, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) finalized its first post-quantum cryptography standards, including module-lattice-based key encapsulation and digital signature schemes, providing a foundation for structured migration in governmental and commercial systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] International organizations and national cybersecurity agencies have published coordinated roadmaps outlining phased adoption timelines, risk assessments, and procurement guidelines to facilitate a systematic transition.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Because the transition to post-quantum cryptography is expected to take many years, organizations increasingly monitor advances in quantum computing to assess whether migration timelines remain appropriate.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Rather than relying on a single measurement, researchers and cybersecurity agencies evaluate multiple technical indicators that together provide a more meaningful assessment of progress toward cryptographically relevant quantum computers (CRQCs).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Physical qubit counts alone are generally considered an incomplete measure of cryptographic capability because large numbers of noisy physical qubits may not be able to perform the long, fault-tolerant computations required for practical cryptanalysis.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Consequently, greater emphasis is often placed on advances in logical qubits, quantum error correction, gate fidelity, circuit depth, and the successful implementation of quantum algorithms such as Shor's algorithm on increasingly complex problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Together, these technical and institutional indicators help governments, industry, and researchers evaluate the pace of quantum computing development and adjust long-term migration strategies as new evidence becomes available.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Digital infrastructures require robust cybersecurity.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Cryptographic systems are vital to protect the confidentiality and authenticity of data.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Quantum computing will be a threat to many of the classical cryptographic algorithms, which are used to achieve these protection goals but are only secure against classical computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Data that is currently not quantum-safe, whether it is stored or transmitted, and that must remain confidential for a long time, may be compromised in the future by quantum computers (“harvest now, decrypt later” attacks).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In addition, authenticity will also be jeopardised by quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The threat that quantum computing poses to cybersecurity can be countered by a timely, comprehensive and coordinated transition to post-quantum cryptography (PQC).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This approach includes cryptographic systems such as learning with errors, ring learning with errors (ring-LWE), the ring learning with errors key exchange and the ring learning with errors signature, the older NTRU or GGH encryption schemes, and the newer NTRU signature and BLISS signatures.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Some of these schemes like NTRU encryption have been studied for many years without anyone finding a feasible attack.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Others like the ring-LWE algorithms have proofs that their security reduces to a worst-case problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission suggested that the Stehle–Steinfeld variant of NTRU be studied for standardization rather than the NTRU algorithm.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Studies have indicated that NTRU may have more secure properties than other lattice based algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Two lattice-based algorithms, ML-KEM (commonly known as Kyber) and ML-DSA (commonly known as Dilithium) were among the first post-quantum algorithms standardised by NIST.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This includes cryptographic systems such as the Unbalanced Oil and Vinegar signature scheme which is based on the difficulty of solving systems of multivariate equations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Various attempts to build secure multivariate equation encryption schemes have been broken, notably the Rainbow signature.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This includes cryptographic systems such as Lamport signatures, the Merkle signature scheme, the XMSS, the SPHINCS, the WOTS and the SPHINCS+ schemes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Hash based digital signatures were invented in the late 1970s by Ralph Merkle and have been studied ever since as an interesting alternative to number-theoretic digital signatures like RSA and DSA.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Their primary drawback is that for any hash-based public key, there is a limit on the number of signatures that can be signed using the corresponding set of private keys.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This fact reduced interest in these signatures until interest was revived due to the desire for cryptography that was resistant to attack by quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There appear to be no patents on the Merkle signature scheme and there exist many non-patented hash functions that could be used with these schemes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The stateful hash-based signature scheme XMSS developed by a team of researchers under the direction of Johannes Buchmann is described in RFC 8391.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Note that all the above schemes are one-time or bounded-time signatures.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Moni Naor and Moti Yung invented UOWHF hashing in 1989 and designed a signature based on hashing (the Naor-Yung scheme) which can be unlimited-time in use (the first such signature that does not require trapdoor properties).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This includes cryptographic systems which rely on error-correcting codes, such as the McEliece and Niederreiter encryption algorithms and the related Courtois, Finiasz and Sendrier Signature scheme.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The original McEliece signature using random Goppa codes has withstood scrutiny for over 40 years.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] However, many variants of the McEliece scheme, which seek to introduce more structure into the code used in order to reduce the size of the keys, have been shown to be insecure.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission has recommended the McEliece public key encryption system as a candidate for long term protection against attacks by quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2025, NIST announced plans to standardize the code-based HQC encryption algorithm.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These cryptographic systems rely on the properties of isogeny graphs of elliptic curves (and higher-dimensional abelian varieties) over finite fields, in particular supersingular isogeny graphs, to create cryptographic systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Another widely noticed construction, *SIDH/SIKE*, was spectacularly broken in 2022.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The attack is however specific to the SIDH/SIKE family of schemes and does not generalize to other isogeny-based constructions.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Using sufficiently large key sizes, the symmetric key cryptographic systems like AES and SNOW 3G are already resistant to attack by a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Further, key management systems and protocols that use symmetric key cryptography instead of public key cryptography, like Kerberos and the 3GPP Mobile Network Authentication Structure, are also inherently secure against attack by a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Given its widespread deployment in the world, some researchers recommend expanded use of Kerberos-like symmetric key management as an efficient way to get post-quantum cryptography today.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In cryptography research, it is desirable to prove the equivalence of a cryptographic algorithm and a known hard mathematical problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These proofs are often called "security reductions", and are used to demonstrate the difficulty of cracking the encryption algorithm.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In other words, the security of a given cryptographic algorithm is reduced to the security of a known hard problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Researchers are actively looking for security reductions in the prospects for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In some versions of Ring-LWE there is a security reduction to the shortest-vector problem (SVP) in a lattice as a lower bound on the security.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Specific ring-LWE systems that have provable security reductions include a variant of Lyubashevsky's ring-LWE signatures defined in a paper by Güneysu, Lyubashevsky, and Pöppelmann.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The GLYPH signature scheme is a variant of the Güneysu, Lyubashevsky, and Pöppelmann (GLP) signature which takes into account research results that have come after the publication of the GLP signature in 2012.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Another Ring-LWE signature is Ring-TESLA.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There also exists a "derandomized variant" of LWE, called Learning with Rounding (LWR), which yields "improved speedup (by eliminating sampling small errors from a Gaussian-like distribution with deterministic errors) and bandwidth".
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] While LWE uses the addition of a small error to conceal the lower bits, LWR uses rounding for the same purpose.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The security of the NTRU encryption scheme and the BLISS signature is believed to be related to, but not provably reducible to, the closest vector problem (CVP) in a lattice.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission suggested that the Stehle–Steinfeld variant of NTRU, which *does* have a security reduction, be studied for long term use instead of the original NTRU algorithm.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Unbalanced Oil and Vinegar signature schemes are asymmetric cryptographic primitives based on multivariate polynomials over a finite field ⁠ $\mathbb {F}$ ⁠.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Bulygin, Petzoldt, and Buchmann have shown a reduction of generic multivariate quadratic UOV systems to the NP-Hard multivariate quadratic equation solving problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2005, Luis Garcia proved that there was a security reduction of Merkle Hash Tree signatures to the security of the underlying hash function.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Garcia showed in his paper that if computationally one-way hash functions exist then the Merkle Hash Tree signature is provably secure.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Therefore, use of a hash function with a provable reduction of security to a known hard problem would have a provable security reduction of the Merkle tree signature to that known hard problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission has recommended use of the Merkle signature scheme for long term security protection against quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The McEliece Encryption System has a security reduction to the syndrome decoding problem (SDP).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Post-Quantum Cryptography Study Group sponsored by the European Commission has recommended the use of this cryptography for long term protection against attack by a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2016, Wang proposed a random linear code encryption scheme RLCE which is based on McEliece schemes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A RLCE scheme can be constructed using any linear code such as Reed-Solomon code by inserting random columns in the underlying linear code generator matrix.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Security is related to the problem of constructing an isogeny between two supersingular curves with the same number of points.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The most recent published investigation of the difficulty of this problem, by Delfs and Galbraith, indicates that this problem is as hard as the inventors of the key exchange suggest that it is.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There is no security reduction to a known NP-hard problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] One common characteristic of many post-quantum cryptography algorithms is that they require larger key sizes than commonly used "pre-quantum" public key algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There are often tradeoffs to be made in key size, computational efficiency and ciphertext or signature size.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The table below lists some values for different schemes at a 128-bit post-quantum security level.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A practical consideration on a choice among post-quantum cryptographic algorithms is the effort required to send public keys over the internet.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] From this point of view, the Ring-LWE, NTRU, and SIDH algorithms provide key sizes conveniently under 1 kB, hash-signature public keys come in under 5 kB, and MDPC-based McEliece takes about 1 kB.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] On the other hand, Goppa-based McEliece requires a nearly 1 MB key.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The fundamental idea of using LWE and Ring LWE for key exchange was proposed and filed at the University of Cincinnati in 2011 by Jintai Ding.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The basic idea comes from the associativity of matrix multiplications, and the errors are used to provide the security.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The paper appeared in 2012 after a provisional patent application was filed in 2012.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2014, Peikert presented a key transport scheme following the same basic idea of Ding's, where the new idea of sending an additional 1 bit signal for rounding in Ding's construction is also used.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] For somewhat greater than 128 bits of security, Singh presents a set of parameters which have 6956-bit public keys for the Peikert's scheme.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The corresponding private key would be roughly 14,000 bits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2015, an authenticated key exchange with provable forward security following the same basic idea of Ding's was presented at Eurocrypt 2015, which is an extension of the HMQV construction in Crypto2005.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The parameters for different security levels from 80 bits to 350 bits, along with the corresponding key sizes are provided in the paper.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] For 128 bits of security in NTRU, `ntruhps2048509` with n = 509 and q = 2048 was selected in the NIST submission in September 2020.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This results in a public key of 699 bytes and a corresponding private key of 935 bytes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In order to get 128 bits of security for hash based signatures to sign 1 million messages using the fractal Merkle tree method of Naor Shenhav and Wool the public and private key sizes are roughly 36,000 bits in length.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] For 128 bits of security in a McEliece scheme, The European Commission's Post-Quantum Cryptography Study group recommends using a binary Goppa code of length at least *n* = 6960 and dimension at least *k* = 5413, and capable of correcting *t* = 119 errors.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] With these parameters the public key for the McEliece system will be a systematic generator matrix whose non-identity part takes *k* × (*n* − *k*) = 8373911 bits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The corresponding private key, which consists of the code support with *n* = 6960 elements from GF(213) and a generator polynomial of with *t* = 119 coefficients from GF(213), will be 92,027 bits in length.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The group is also investigating the use of Quasi-cyclic MDPC codes of length at least *n* = 216 + 6 = 65542 and dimension at least *k* = 215 + 3 = 32771, and capable of correcting *t* = 264 errors.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] With these parameters the public key for the McEliece system will be the first row of a systematic generator matrix whose non-identity part takes *k* = 32771 bits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The private key, a quasi-cyclic parity-check matrix with *d* = 274 nonzero entries on a column (or twice as much on a row), takes no more than *d* × 16 = 4384 bits when represented as the coordinates of the nonzero entries on the first row.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Barreto et al. recommend using a binary Goppa code of length at least *n* = 3307 and dimension at least *k* = 2515, and capable of correcting *t* = 66 errors.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] With these parameters the public key for the McEliece system will be a systematic generator matrix whose non-identity part takes *k* × (*n* − *k*) = 1991880 bits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The corresponding private key, which consists of the code support with *n* = 3307 elements from GF(212) and a generator polynomial of *t* = 66 coefficients from GF(212), will be 40,476 bits in length.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] For 128 bits of security in the supersingular isogeny Diffie–Hellman (SIDH) method, De Feo, Jao and Plut recommend using a supersingular curve modulo of a 768-bit prime.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] If one uses elliptic curve point compression, the public key will need to be no more than 8x768 or 6144 bits in length.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This makes the number of bits transmitted roughly equivalent to the non-quantum secure RSA and Diffie–Hellman at the same classical security level.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] As a general rule, for 128 bits of security in a symmetric-key–based system, one can safely use key sizes of 256 bits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The best quantum attack against arbitrary symmetric-key systems is an application of Grover's algorithm, which requires work proportional to the square root of the size of the key space.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] To transmit an encrypted key to a device that possesses the symmetric key necessary to decrypt that key requires roughly 256 bits as well.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] It is clear that symmetric-key systems offer the smallest key sizes for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A public-key system demonstrates a property referred to as perfect forward secrecy when it generates random public keys per session for the purposes of key agreement.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This means that the compromise of one message cannot lead to the compromise of others, and also that there is not a single secret value which can lead to the compromise of multiple messages.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Security experts recommend using cryptographic algorithms that support forward secrecy over those that do not.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The reason for this is that forward secrecy can protect against the compromise of long term private keys associated with public/private key pairs.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This is viewed as a means of preventing mass surveillance by intelligence agencies.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Both the Ring-LWE key exchange and supersingular isogeny Diffie–Hellman (SIDH) key exchange can support forward secrecy in one exchange with the other party.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Both the Ring-LWE and SIDH can also be used without forward secrecy by creating a variant of the classic ElGamal encryption variant of Diffie–Hellman.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The other algorithms in this article, such as NTRU, do not support forward secrecy as is.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Any authenticated public key encryption system can be used to build a key exchange with forward secrecy.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The **Open Quantum Safe** (**OQS**) project was started in late 2016 and has the goal of developing and prototyping quantum-resistant cryptography.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] It aims to integrate current post-quantum schemes in one library: **liboqs**. liboqs is an open source C library for quantum-resistant cryptographic algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] It initially focuses on key exchange algorithms but by now includes several signature schemes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] It provides a common application programming interface (API) suitable for post-quantum key exchange algorithms, and will collect together various implementations. liboqs will also include a test harness and benchmarking routines to compare performance of post-quantum implementations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Furthermore, OQS also provides integration of liboqs into OpenSSL.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] A challenge in post-quantum cryptography is the implementation of potentially quantum safe algorithms into existing systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] There are tests done, for example by Microsoft Research implementing PICNIC in a PKI using Hardware security modules.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Test implementations for Google's NewHope algorithm have also been done by HSM vendors.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In August 2023, Google released a FIDO2 security key implementation of an ECC/Dilithium hybrid signature schema which was done in partnership with ETH Zürich.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Signal Protocol has used Post-Quantum Extended Diffie–Hellman (PQXDH) since 2023.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] On February 21, 2024, Apple announced that they were going to upgrade their iMessage protocol with a new PQC protocol called "PQ3", which will use ongoing keying.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple stated that, although capable quantum computers do not yet exist, they wanted to mitigate risks from future quantum computers as well as so-called "Harvest now, decrypt later" attack scenarios.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple stated that they believe their PQ3 implementation provides protections that "surpass those in all other widely deployed messaging apps", because it uses ongoing keying.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple intended to replace the existing iMessage protocol within all supported conversations with PQ3 by the end of 2024.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple also defined a scale to make it easier to compare the security properties of messaging apps, with a scale represented by levels ranging from 0 to 3: 0 for no end-to-end by default, 1 for pre-quantum end-to-end by default, 2 for PQC key establishment only (e.g.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] PQXDH), and 3 for PQC key establishment *and* ongoing rekeying (PQ3).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The Internet Engineering Task Force has prepared an Internet-Draft using PQC algorithms in Messaging Layer Security (MLS).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] MLS will be used in RCS text messaging in Google Messages and Messages (Apple).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Blockchain systems commonly rely on public-key cryptography, particularly elliptic-curve digital signature algorithms (ECDSA), to authenticate transactions and control asset ownership.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These cryptographic schemes are vulnerable to quantum attacks, as Shor’s algorithm can efficiently solve the discrete logarithm problem on which they are based.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In many blockchain protocols, public keys are not revealed until a transaction is executed; however, once exposed, they may become susceptible to quantum attacks if adversaries possess sufficiently advanced quantum capabilities.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This has led to recommendations that users migrate assets to quantum-resistant address schemes prior to the emergence of large-scale quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The integration of post-quantum cryptographic algorithms into blockchain systems presents several technical challenges.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Many post-quantum signature schemes require larger key and signature sizes, which can increase transaction size, storage requirements, and network bandwidth usage.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Additionally, higher computational costs for verification may affect scalability and throughput in distributed networks.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Hybrid cryptographic approaches combining classical and post-quantum signatures have been proposed as transitional solutions.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These approaches aim to maintain backward compatibility while gradually introducing quantum-resistant security mechanisms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Ongoing research is focused on optimizing post-quantum schemes for decentralized environments while balancing security, efficiency, and scalability requirements.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] While post-quantum algorithms protect data content from future decryption, they do not prevent the interception and storage of the encrypted ciphertext itself (a threat model known as "Harvest now, decrypt later").
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] To mitigate this risk, some network architectures incorporate physical layer security (PLS) or optical chaos alongside PQC.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] By burying the optical signal within the noise floor (negative OSNR) using spectral phase encoding, these physical countermeasures aim to make the transmission unrecordable.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This creates a "defense-in-depth" strategy: physical obfuscation prevents the harvesting of ciphertext entirely, ensuring that no data exists for future quantum decryption, while PQC algorithms provide necessary protection for data stored at the endpoints.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Google has maintained the use of "hybrid encryption" in its use of post-quantum cryptography: whenever a relatively new post-quantum scheme is used, it is combined with a more proven, non-PQ scheme.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This is to ensure that the data are not compromised even if the relatively new PQ algorithm turns out to be vulnerable to non-quantum attacks before Y2Q.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] This type of scheme is used in its 2016 and 2019 tests for post-quantum TLS, and in its 2023 FIDO2 key.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] One of the algorithms used in the 2019 test, SIKE, was broken in 2022, but the non-PQ X25519 layer (already used widely in TLS) still protected the data.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Apple's PQ3 and Signal's PQXDH are also hybrid.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] The NSA and GCHQ argue against hybrid encryption, claiming that it adds complexity to implementation and transition.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Bernstein, who supports hybrid encryption, argues that the claims are bogus.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Post-quantum cryptography's need is predicated on traditional, established cryptographic problems being quickly solved by a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] However, quantum computers are still under development, and have yet to demonstrate a large scale test of Shor's algorithm, verifying that a quantum speed-up mechanism is possible, and out-performs a classical computer on such problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2019, a team using the *IBM Q* quantum computer could factor the numbers 15 and 21, but *not* 35.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Other attempts have been made to simulate quantum computers for larger numbers, but the simulations had no quantum advantage (i.e a speed-up over a classical computer).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] These cryptograpic systems are used worldwide, and have been extensively tested for vulnerabilities for several decades.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Mathematicians Stephen Wolfram and Christopher Wolfram have created simulated models based on Branchial Graphs to mimic quantum mechanics, and by extension can emulate systems utilized by quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Their research lead Stephen to publicly express mild doubts about the proposed *quantum speed-up mechanism*'s existence, related to the systematic collapse/unwinding of the entangle quantum states down to a usable, error-corrected solution.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] That is, *doubts* about the mechanism responsible for the *theoretical quantum advantage* utilized by future quantum computers, at scale, where a large number of fully entangled qubits are capable of running Shor's Algorithm against a modern classical problem (e.g.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] RSA-2048, utilizing *integer factorization*).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] In 2013, Edward Snowden's NSA leaks confirmed that the largest supercomputers of the time could not break *correctly implemented* public key crypto systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Also, the NSA had not found a mathematical shortcut, despite being the largest employer of mathematicians in the world.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Security analyst and cryptographer, Bruce Schneier, who had access to the Snowden archive, concluded that the math was never broken.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/post-quantum-cryptography] Taken in aggregate, if the above criticisms prove to be true, then the need for *post-quantum cryptography* is put into question, along with the need to switch modern business infrastructure onto *less-proven* cryptographic schemes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A **quantum computer** is a real or theoretical computer that exploits quantum phenomena like superposition and entanglement in an essential way.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] It is widely believed that a quantum computer could perform *some* calculations exponentially faster than any classical computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] For example, a large-scale quantum computer could break some widely used encryption schemes and aid physicists in performing physical simulations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] However, current hardware implementations of quantum computation are largely experimental and only suitable for specialized tasks.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The basic unit of information in quantum computing, the qubit (or "quantum bit"), serves the same function as the bit in ordinary or "classical" computing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] However, unlike a classical bit, which can be in one of two states (a binary), a qubit can exist in a linear combination of two states known as a quantum superposition.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The result of measuring a qubit is one of the two states given by a probabilistic rule.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] If a quantum computer manipulates the qubit in a particular way, wave interference effects amplify the probability of the desired measurement result.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The design of quantum algorithms involves creating procedures that allow a quantum computer to perform this amplification.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computers are not yet practical for real-world applications.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Physically engineering high-quality qubits has proven to be challenging.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] If a physical qubit is not sufficiently isolated from its environment, it suffers from quantum decoherence, introducing noise into calculations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] National governments have invested heavily in experimental research aimed at developing scalable qubits with longer coherence times and lower error rates.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Example implementations include superconductors (which isolate an electrical current by eliminating electrical resistance) and ion traps (which confine a single atomic particle using electromagnetic fields).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Researchers have claimed, and are widely believed to be correct, that certain quantum devices can outperform classical computers on narrowly defined tasks, a milestone referred to as quantum advantage or quantum supremacy.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] These tasks are not necessarily useful for real-world applications.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] As a result, current demonstrations are best understood as scientific milestones rather than evidence of broad near-term deployment.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In December 2024, Google's Willow chip achieved below-threshold error correction, a milestone 30 years in the making, while global government investment in quantum computing reached $10 billion by April 2025.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] For many years, the fields of quantum mechanics and computer science formed distinct academic communities.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Modern quantum theory was developed in the 1920s to explain perplexing physical phenomena observed at atomic scales, and digital computers emerged in the following decades to replace human computers for tedious calculations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Both disciplines had practical applications during World War II; computers played a major role in wartime cryptography, and quantum physics was essential for nuclear physics used in the Manhattan Project.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] As physicists applied quantum mechanical models to computational problems and swapped digital bits for qubits, the fields of quantum mechanics and computer science began to converge.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In 1980, Paul Benioff introduced the quantum Turing machine, which uses quantum theory to describe a simplified computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] When digital computers became faster, physicists faced an exponential increase in overhead when simulating quantum dynamics, prompting Yuri Manin and Richard Feynman to independently suggest that hardware based on quantum phenomena might be more efficient for computer simulation.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In a 1984 paper, Charles Bennett and Gilles Brassard applied quantum theory to cryptography protocols and demonstrated that quantum key distribution could enhance information security.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum algorithms then emerged for solving oracle problems, such as Deutsch's algorithm in 1985, the Bernstein–Vazirani algorithm in 1993, and Simon's algorithm in 1994.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] These algorithms did not solve practical problems, but demonstrated mathematically that one could obtain more information by querying a black box with a quantum state in superposition, sometimes referred to as *quantum parallelism*.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Peter Shor built on these results with his 1994 algorithm for breaking the widely used RSA and Diffie–Hellman encryption protocols, which drew significant attention to the field of quantum computing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In 1996, Grover's algorithm established a quantum speedup for the widely applicable unstructured search problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The same year, Seth Lloyd proved that quantum computers could simulate quantum systems without the exponential overhead present in classical simulations, validating Feynman's 1982 conjecture.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Over the years, experimentalists have constructed small-scale quantum computers using trapped ions and superconductors.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In 1998, a two-qubit quantum computer demonstrated the feasibility of the technology, and subsequent experiments have increased the number of qubits and reduced error rates.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Recent milestones in quantum computing have increasingly focused on controlling decoherence through quantum error correction.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In 2024, researchers demonstrated theoretical and practical approaches for high threshold, low-overhead fault-tolerant quantum memory.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] These developments represent a critical step toward scaling systems beyond the noisy intermediate-scale quantum (NISQ) era into reliable, fault-tolerant computing architectures, though large-scale physical implementation remains an ongoing engineering challenge.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Computer engineers typically describe a modern computer's operation in terms of classical electrodynamics.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In these "classical" computers, some components (such as semiconductors and random number generators) may rely on quantum behavior; however, because they are not isolated from their environment, any quantum information eventually quickly decoheres.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] While programmers may depend on probability theory when designing a randomized algorithm, quantum-mechanical notions such as superposition and wave interference are largely irrelevant in program analysis.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The "classical" in *classical computation* thus refers to the computational model, not to whether the microscopic physics of the hardware is ultimately quantum-mechanical.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A conventional digital computer can be described by classical states and transition rules: memory stores bits, while logic elements transform one configuration of bits into another.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This computational behavior is not tied to electronics, and can be abstracted through the idea of a Turing machine, a mechanical device that performs deterministic transformations on a finite state.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In principle, the same classical transition rules can be implemented by some entirely classical mechanical device, possibly with a fixed slow-down in physical time.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] If a classical computation uses randomness, this can be modeled as access to random classical bits rather than as coherent quantum information.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum computer, by contrast, uses coherent quantum states, so that superposition, relative phase, and interference are part of the computation itself, and has no classical counterpart.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum programs instead rely on precise control of coherent quantum systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Physicists describe these systems mathematically using linear algebra.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Complex numbers model probability amplitudes, vectors model quantum states, and matrices model the operations that can be performed on these states.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Programming a quantum computer is then a matter of composing operations in such a way that the resulting program computes a useful result in theory and is implementable in practice.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Just as the bit is the basic concept of classical information theory, the *qubit* is the fundamental unit of quantum information.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The same term *qubit* is used to refer to an abstract mathematical model and to any physical system that is represented by that model.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A classical bit, by definition, exists in either of two physical states, which can be denoted 0 and 1.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A qubit is also described by a state, and two states, often written $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ , serve as the quantum counterparts of the classical states 0 and 1.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] However, the quantum states $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ belong to a vector space, meaning that they can be multiplied by constants and added together, and the result is again a valid quantum state.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Such a combination is known as a *superposition* of $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A two-dimensional vector mathematically represents a qubit state.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Physicists typically use bra–ket notation for quantum mechanical linear algebra, writing $|\psi \rangle$ 'ket psi' for a vector labeled $\psi$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Because a qubit is a two-state system, any qubit state takes the form $\alpha |0\rangle +\beta |1\rangle$ , where $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ are the standard *basis states*, and $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are the *probability amplitudes,* which are in general complex numbers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] If either $\alpha$ or $\beta$ is zero, the qubit is effectively a classical bit; when both are nonzero, the qubit is in superposition.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Such a quantum state vector behaves similarly to a (classical) probability vector, with one key difference: unlike probabilities, probability *amplitudes* are not necessarily positive numbers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Negative amplitudes allow for destructive wave interference.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] When a qubit is measured in the standard basis, the result is a classical bit.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The Born rule describes the norm-squared correspondence between amplitudes and probabilities—when measuring a qubit $\alpha |0\rangle +\beta |1\rangle$ , the state collapses to $|0\rangle$ with probability $|\alpha |^{2}$ , or to $|1\rangle$ with probability $|\beta |^{2}$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Any valid qubit state has coefficients $\alpha$ and $\beta$ such that $|\alpha |^{2}+|\beta |^{2}=1$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] As an example, measuring the qubit $1/{\sqrt {2}}|0\rangle +1/{\sqrt {2}}|1\rangle$ would produce either $|0\rangle$ or $|1\rangle$ with equal probability.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Each additional qubit doubles the dimension of the state space.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This vector inhabits a four-dimensional vector space spanned by the basis vectors |00⟩, |01⟩, |10⟩, and |11⟩.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In general, the vector space for an n-qubit system is 2*n*-dimensional, and this makes it challenging for a classical computer to simulate a quantum one: representing a 100-qubit system requires storing 2100 classical values.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The state of this one-qubit quantum memory can be manipulated by applying quantum logic gates, analogous to how classical memory can be manipulated with classical logic gates.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] One important gate for both classical and quantum computation is the NOT gate, which can be represented by a matrix $X:={\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{pmatrix}}.$ Mathematically, the application of such a logic gate to a quantum state vector is modeled with matrix multiplication.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The mathematics of single-qubit gates can be extended to operate on multi-qubit quantum memories in two important ways.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] One way is simply to select a qubit and apply that gate to the target qubit while leaving the remainder of the memory unaffected.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Another way is to apply the gate to its target only if another part of the memory is in a desired state.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] These two choices can be illustrated using another example.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In other words, the CNOT applies a NOT gate ( ${\textstyle X}$ from before) to the second qubit if and only if the first qubit is in the state ${\textstyle |1\rangle }$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] If the first qubit is ${\textstyle |0\rangle }$ , nothing is done to either qubit.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In summary, quantum computation can be described as a network of quantum logic gates and measurements.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] However, any measurement can be deferred to the end of quantum computation, though this deferment may come at a computational cost, so most quantum circuits depict a network consisting only of quantum logic gates and no measurements.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] There are multiple models of computation for quantum computing, distinguished by the basic elements in which the computation is decomposed.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum gate array decomposes computation into a sequence of few-qubit quantum gates.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum computation can be described as a network of quantum logic gates and measurements.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Any quantum computation (which is, in the above formalism, any unitary matrix of size $2^{n}\times 2^{n}$ over n qubits) can be represented as a network of quantum logic gates from a fairly small family of gates.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A choice of gate family that enables this construction is known as a universal gate set, since a computer that can run such circuits is a universal quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] One common such set includes all single-qubit gates as well as the CNOT gate from above.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This means any quantum computation can be performed by executing a sequence of single-qubit gates together with CNOT gates.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Though this gate set is infinite, it can be replaced with a finite gate set by appealing to the Solovay-Kitaev theorem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Implementation of Boolean functions using the few-qubit quantum gates is presented here.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A measurement-based quantum computer decomposes computation into a sequence of Bell state measurements and single-qubit quantum gates applied to a highly entangled initial state (a cluster state), using a technique called quantum gate teleportation.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] An adiabatic quantum computer, based on quantum annealing, decomposes computation into a slow continuous transformation of an initial Hamiltonian into a final Hamiltonian, whose ground states contain the solution.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Neuromorphic quantum computing (abbreviated 'n.quantum computing') is an unconventional process of computing that uses neuromorphic computing to perform quantum operations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] It was suggested that quantum algorithms, which are algorithms that run on a realistic model of quantum computation, can be computed equally efficiently with neuromorphic quantum computing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Both traditional quantum computing and neuromorphic quantum computing are physics-based unconventional computing approaches to computations and do not follow the von Neumann architecture.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] They both construct a system (a circuit) that represents the physical problem at hand and then leverage their respective physics properties of the system to seek the "minimum".
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Neuromorphic quantum computing and quantum computing share similar physical properties during computation.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A topological quantum computer decomposes computation into the braiding of anyons in a 2D lattice.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum Turing machine is the quantum analog of a Turing machine.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This equivalence need not hold for practical quantum computers, since the overhead of simulation may be too large to be practical.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The threshold theorem shows how increasing the number of qubits can mitigate errors, yet fully fault-tolerant quantum computing remains "a rather distant dream".
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] According to some researchers, *noisy intermediate-scale quantum* (NISQ) machines may have specialized uses in the near future, but noise in quantum gates limits their reliability.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Scientists at Harvard University successfully created "quantum circuits" that correct errors more efficiently than alternative methods, which may potentially remove a major obstacle to practical quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The Harvard research team was supported by MIT, QuEra Computing, Caltech, and Princeton University and funded by DARPA's Optimization with Noisy Intermediate-Scale Quantum devices (ONISQ) program.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Digital cryptography enables communications to remain private, preventing unauthorized parties from accessing them.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Conventional encryption, the obscuring of a message with a key through an algorithm, relies on the algorithm being difficult to reverse.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Encryption is also the basis for digital signatures and authentication mechanisms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computing may be sufficiently more powerful that difficult reversals are feasible, allowing messages relying on conventional encryption to be read.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum cryptography replaces conventional algorithms with computations based on quantum computing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In principle, quantum encryption would be impossible to decode even with a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This advantage comes at a significant cost in terms of elaborate infrastructure, while effectively preventing legitimate decoding of messages by governmental security officials.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Ongoing research in quantum and post-quantum cryptography has led to new algorithms for quantum key distribution, initial work on quantum random number generation and to some early technology demonstrations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum cryptography enables new ways to transmit data securely; for example, quantum key distribution uses entangled quantum states to establish secure cryptographic keys.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] When a sender and receiver exchange quantum states, they can guarantee that an adversary does not intercept the message, as any unauthorized eavesdropper would disturb the delicate quantum system and introduce a detectable change.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] With appropriate cryptographic protocols, the sender and receiver can thus establish shared private information resistant to eavesdropping.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Modern fiber-optic cables can transmit quantum information over relatively short distances.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Ongoing experimental research aims to develop more reliable hardware (such as quantum repeaters), hoping to scale this technology to long-distance quantum networks with end-to-end entanglement.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Theoretically, this could enable novel technological applications, such as distributed quantum computing and enhanced quantum sensing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum teleportation is a protocol by which Alice can transmit the quantum state of a qubit to Bob using one shared entangled pair (e-bit) and two classical bits of communication.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The state of Alice's qubit is not physically transmitted—instead, it is reconstructed at Bob's end through classically communicated measurement outcomes and local unitary corrections.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This demonstrates that quantum communication requires both entanglement and classical communication; neither alone is sufficient.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Teleportation cannot be used to transmit information faster than light because the classical bits must travel through normal channels.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Superdense coding is the complementary protocol: using one shared e-bit and sending only one qubit, Alice can transmit two classical bits to Bob.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This appears to violate Holevo's theorem—which states that a single qubit can carry at most one bit of classical information—but the shared entanglement circumvents this limit.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Superdense coding thus demonstrates that entanglement can effectively double the classical information-carrying capacity of quantum communication.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Progress in finding quantum algorithms typically focuses on the quantum circuit model, though exceptions like the quantum adiabatic algorithm exist.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum algorithms can be roughly categorized by the type of speedup achieved over corresponding classical algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] These algorithms depend on the primitive of the quantum Fourier transform.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] No mathematical proof has been found that shows that an equally fast classical algorithm cannot be discovered, but evidence suggests that this is unlikely.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Certain oracle problems like Simon's problem and the Bernstein–Vazirani problem do give provable speedups, though this is in the quantum query model, which is a restricted model where lower bounds are much easier to prove and don't necessarily translate to speedups for practical problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Because these problems are BQP-complete, an equally fast classical algorithm for them would imply that "no quantum algorithm" provides a super-polynomial speedup, which is believed to be unlikely.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Some quantum algorithms, such as Grover's algorithm and amplitude amplification, give polynomial speedups over corresponding classical algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Though these algorithms give comparably modest quadratic speedup, they are widely applicable and thus give speedups for a wide range of problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] These speed-ups are, however, over the theoretical worst-case of classical algorithms, and concrete real-world speed-ups over algorithms used in practice have not been demonstrated.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Since chemistry and nanotechnology rely on understanding quantum systems, and such systems are impossible to simulate in an efficient manner classically, quantum simulation may be an important application of quantum computing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Recent reviews identify quantum chemistry as one of the most promising application areas for quantum computing, particularly for problems in electronic structure, chemical dynamics, and spectroscopy, while noting that useful implementations remain limited by current hardware.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum simulation could also be used to simulate the behavior of atoms and particles at unusual conditions such as the reactions inside a collider.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In June 2023, IBM computer scientists reported that a quantum computer produced better results for a physics problem than a conventional supercomputer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] About 2% of the annual global energy output is used for nitrogen fixation to produce ammonia for the Haber process in the agricultural fertiliser industry (even though naturally occurring organisms also produce ammonia).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum simulations might be used to understand this process and increase the energy efficiency of production.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] It is expected that an early use of quantum computing will be modeling that improves the efficiency of the Haber–Bosch process by the mid-2020s although some have predicted it will take longer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A notable application of quantum computing is in attacking cryptographic systems that are currently in use.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Integer factorization, which underpins the security of public key cryptographic systems, is believed to be computationally infeasible on a classical computer for large integers if they are the product of a few prime numbers (e.g., the product of two 300-digit primes).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] By contrast, a quantum computer could solve this problem exponentially faster using Shor's algorithm to factor the integer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This ability would allow a quantum computer to break many of the cryptographic systems in use today, in the sense that there would be a polynomial time (in the number of digits of the integer) algorithm for solving the problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In particular, most of the popular public key ciphers are based on the difficulty of factoring integers or the discrete logarithm problem, both of which can be solved by Shor's algorithm.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In particular, the RSA, Diffie–Hellman, and elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman algorithms could be broken.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] These are used to protect secure Web pages, encrypted email, and many other types of data.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Breaking these would have significant ramifications for electronic privacy and security.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Identifying cryptographic systems that may be secure against quantum algorithms is an actively researched topic under the field of *post-quantum cryptography*.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Some public-key algorithms are based on problems other than the integer factorization and discrete logarithm problems to which Shor's algorithm applies, such as the McEliece cryptosystem, which relies on a hard problem in coding theory.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Lattice-based cryptosystems are also not known to be broken by quantum computers, and finding a polynomial time algorithm for solving the dihedral hidden subgroup problem, which would break many lattice-based cryptosystems, is a well-studied open problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The most well-known example of a problem that allows for a polynomial quantum speedup is *unstructured search*, which involves finding a marked item out of a list of n items in a database.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] This can be solved by Grover's algorithm using $O({\sqrt {n}})$ queries to the database, quadratically fewer than the $\Omega (n)$ queries required for classical algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In this case, the advantage is not only provable but also optimal: it has been shown that Grover's algorithm gives the maximal possible probability of finding the desired element for any number of oracle lookups.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Many examples of provable quantum speedups for query problems are based on Grover's algorithm, including Brassard, Høyer, and Tapp's algorithm for finding collisions in two-to-one functions, and Farhi, Goldstone, and Gutmann's algorithm for evaluating NAND trees.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] There exists a Boolean function that evaluates each input and determines whether it is the correct answer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] For problems with all these properties, the running time of Grover's algorithm on a quantum computer scales as the square root of the number of inputs (or elements in the database), as opposed to the linear scaling of classical algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A general class of problems to which Grover's algorithm can be applied is a Boolean satisfiability problem, where the *database* through which the algorithm iterates is that of all possible answers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] An example and possible application of this is a password cracker that attempts to guess a password.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Breaking symmetric ciphers with this algorithm is of interest to government agencies.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum annealing uses the adiabatic theorem to perform calculations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] A system is placed in the ground state for a simple Hamiltonian, which slowly evolves to a more complicated Hamiltonian whose ground state represents the solution to the problem in question.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] The adiabatic theorem states that if the evolution is slow enough, the system will stay in its ground state at all times through the process.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum annealing can solve Ising models and the (computationally equivalent) QUBO problem, which in turn can be used to encode a wide range of combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Adiabatic optimization may be helpful for solving computational biology problems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Since quantum computers can produce outputs that classical computers cannot produce efficiently, and since quantum computation is fundamentally linear algebraic, some express hope in developing quantum algorithms that can speed up machine learning tasks.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] However, review literature notes that many proposed quantum machine-learning advantages rely on assumptions about efficient data encoding or continued access to quantum hardware, and have not yet translated into broad practical end-to-end advantage on current devices.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] For example, the HHL Algorithm, named after its discoverers Harrow, Hassidim, and Lloyd, is believed to provide speedup over classical counterparts.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Some research groups have recently explored the use of quantum annealing hardware for training Boltzmann machines and deep neural networks.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Deep generative chemistry models have been explored for potential applications in drug discovery.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Early experimental work has explored the use of near-term quantum hardware in molecular generative modeling for drug discovery.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] However, the immense size and complexity of the structural space of all possible drug-like molecules pose significant obstacles, which could be overcome in the future by quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computers are naturally good for solving complex quantum many-body problems and thus may be instrumental in applications involving quantum chemistry.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Therefore, one can expect that quantum-enhanced generative models including quantum GANs may eventually be developed into ultimate generative chemistry algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] Artificial intelligence has also been explored as a tool for discovering and optimizing algorithms relevant to quantum computing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] AlphaEvolve, a Google DeepMind system based on large language models and evolutionary algorithms, has been described as a coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p01] In quantum-computing research, AlphaEvolve-optimized quantum circuits have been used in work on quantum computation of molecular geometry through many-body nuclear spin echoes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] As of 2023, classical computers outperform quantum computers for all real-world applications.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] While current quantum computers may speed up solutions to particular mathematical problems, they give no computational advantage for practical tasks.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Scientists and engineers are exploring multiple technologies for quantum computing hardware and hope to develop scalable quantum architectures, but serious obstacles remain.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In practice, improvements in qubit counts alone are not enough, because error rates, connectivity, and data movement also affect whether an end-to-end application can outperform classical methods.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] There are a number of technical challenges in building a large-scale quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The control of multi-qubit systems requires the generation and coordination of a large number of electrical signals with tight and deterministic timing resolution.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] This has led to the development of quantum controllers that enable interfacing with the qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Scaling these systems to support a growing number of qubits is an additional challenge.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The theoretical potential for large-scale quantum computers to eventually break widely used public-key encryption schemes has prompted significant motivated changes in global cybersecurity strategies.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In response to this future challenge, organizations, including the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), have initiated detailed standardization processes for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] These global efforts are designed to develop, evaluate, and deploy cryptographic algorithms that remain safe against both quantum and classical computer attacks, well before fully fault-tolerant quantum systems become available.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Sourcing parts for quantum computers is also very difficult.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Superconducting quantum computers, like those constructed by Google and IBM, need helium-3, a nuclear research byproduct, and special superconducting cables made only by the Japanese company Coax Co.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] On 27 January 2026, the US DARPA agency made a call for proposals for a quantum computing coolant below 1 kelvin, which does not use helium-3.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In February 2026, the Chinese Academy of Sciences announced the testing of a rare-earth alloy, EuCo2Al9, which could fill a similar role.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] One of the greatest challenges involved in constructing quantum computers is controlling or removing quantum decoherence.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] This usually means isolating the system from its environment, as interactions with the external world cause the system to decohere.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] However, other sources of decoherence also exist.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Examples include the quantum gates, the lattice vibrations, and the background thermonuclear spin of the physical system used to implement the qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Decoherence is irreversible, as it is effectively non-unitary, and is usually something that should be highly controlled, if not avoided.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Decoherence times for candidate systems in particular, the transverse relaxation time *T*2 (for NMR and MRI technology, also called the *dephasing time*), typically range between nanoseconds and seconds at low temperatures.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Currently, some quantum computers require their qubits to be cooled to 20 millikelvin (usually using a dilution refrigerator) in order to prevent significant decoherence.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] A 2020 study argues that ionizing radiation such as cosmic rays can nevertheless cause certain systems to decohere within milliseconds.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] As a result, time-consuming tasks may render some quantum algorithms inoperable, as attempting to maintain the state of qubits for a long enough duration will eventually corrupt the superpositions.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] These issues are more difficult for optical approaches as the timescales are orders of magnitude shorter, and an often-cited approach to overcoming them is optical pulse shaping.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Error rates are typically proportional to the ratio of operating time to decoherence time; hence, any operation must be completed much more quickly than the decoherence time.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] As described by the threshold theorem, if the error rate is small enough, it is thought to be possible to use quantum error correction to suppress errors and decoherence.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] This allows the total calculation time to be longer than the decoherence time if the error correction scheme can correct errors faster than decoherence introduces them.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] An often-cited figure for the required error rate in each gate for fault-tolerant computation is 10−3, assuming the noise is depolarizing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Meeting this scalability condition is possible for a wide range of systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] However, the use of error correction brings with it the cost of a greatly increased number of required qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The number required to factor integers using Shor's algorithm is still polynomial, and thought to be between L and *L*2, where L is the number of binary digits in the number to be factored; error correction algorithms would inflate this figure by an additional factor of L.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] For a 1000-bit number, this implies a need for about 104 bits without error correction.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] With error correction, the figure would rise to about 107 bits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Computation time is about *L*2 or about 107 steps and at 1 MHz, about 10 seconds.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] However, the encoding and error-correction overheads increase the size of a real fault-tolerant quantum computer by several orders of magnitude.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Careful estimates show that at least 3 million physical qubits would factor 2,048-bit integer in 5 months on a fully error-corrected trapped-ion quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In terms of the number of physical qubits, to date, this remains the lowest estimate for practically useful integer factorization problem sizing 1,024-bit or larger.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] One approach to overcoming errors combines low-density parity-check code with cat qubits that have intrinsic bit-flip error suppression.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Implementing 100 logical qubits with 768 cat qubits could reduce the error rate to one part in 108 per cycle per bit.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Another approach to the stability-decoherence problem is to create a topological quantum computer with anyons, quasi-particles used as threads, and relying on braid theory to form stable logic gates.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Non-Abelian anyons can, in effect, remember how they have been manipulated, making them potentially useful in quantum computing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] As of 2025, Microsoft and other organizations are investing in quasi-particle research.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Physicist John Preskill coined the term *quantum supremacy* to describe the engineering feat of demonstrating that a programmable quantum device can solve a problem beyond the capabilities of state-of-the-art classical computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The problem need not be useful, so some view the quantum supremacy test only as a potential future benchmark.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In October 2019, Google AI Quantum, with the help of NASA, became the first to claim to have achieved quantum supremacy by performing calculations on the Sycamore quantum computer more than 3,000,000 times faster than they could be done on Summit, generally considered the world's fastest computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In December 2020, a group at USTC implemented a type of boson sampling on 76 photons with a photonic quantum computer, Jiuzhang, to demonstrate quantum supremacy.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The authors claim that a classical contemporary supercomputer would require a computational time of 600 million years to generate the number of samples their quantum processor can generate in 20 seconds.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Claims of quantum supremacy have generated hype around quantum computing, but they are based on contrived benchmark tasks that do not directly imply useful real-world applications.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Accordingly, benchmark-level quantum advantage should not be interpreted as proof that quantum computers are already broadly useful across practical computing workloads.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Despite high hopes for quantum computing, significant progress in hardware, and optimism about future applications, a 2023 Nature spotlight article summarized current quantum computers as being "For now, [good for] absolutely nothing".
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The article elaborated that quantum computers are yet to be more useful or efficient than conventional computers in any case, though it also argued that, in the long term, such computers are likely to be useful.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] A 2023 Communications of the ACM article found that current quantum computing algorithms are "insufficient for practical quantum advantage without significant improvements across the software/hardware stack".
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] It argues that the most promising candidates for achieving speedup with quantum computers are "small-data problems", for example, in chemistry and materials science.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] This state of affairs can be traced to several current and long-term considerations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In particular, building computers with large numbers of qubits may be futile if those qubits are not connected well enough and cannot maintain a sufficiently high degree of entanglement for a long time.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] When trying to outperform conventional computers, quantum computing researchers often look for new tasks that can be solved on quantum computers, but this leaves the possibility that efficient non-quantum techniques will be developed in response, as seen for Quantum supremacy demonstrations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Therefore, it is desirable to prove lower bounds on the complexity of best possible non-quantum algorithms (which may be unknown) and show that some quantum algorithms asymptotically improve upon those bounds.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Bill Unruh doubted the practicality of quantum computers in a paper published in 1994.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Paul Davies argued that a 400-qubit computer would even come into conflict with the cosmological information bound implied by the holographic principle.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Skeptics like Gil Kalai doubt that quantum supremacy will ever be achieved.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] continuously variable parameters defining the quantum state of such a system?
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] A practical quantum computer must use a physical system as a programmable quantum register.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Researchers are exploring several technologies as candidates for reliable qubit implementations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Superconductors and trapped ions are some of the most developed proposals, but experimentalists are considering other hardware possibilities as well.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] For example, topological quantum computer approaches are being explored for more fault-tolerance computing systems.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The first quantum logic gates were implemented with trapped ions and prototype general-purpose machines with up to 20 qubits have been realized.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] However, the technology behind these devices combines complex vacuum equipment, lasers, and microwave and radio frequency equipment, making full-scale processors difficult to integrate with standard computing equipment.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Moreover, the trapped ion system itself has engineering challenges to overcome.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The largest commercial systems are based on superconductor devices and have scaled to 2000 qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] However, the error rates for larger machines have been on the order of 5%.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Technologically, these devices are all cryogenic and scaling to large numbers of qubits requires wafer-scale integration, a serious engineering challenge by itself.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In addition to cryogenic platforms, room-temperature approaches to spin–photon interfaces have been experimentally demonstrated.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Such room-temperature, chip-integrated spin–photon interfaces are being investigated as potential building blocks for heterogeneous quantum networks that combine different qubit modalities and reduce reliance on large cryogenic infrastructures.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Any computational problem solvable by a classical computer is also solvable by a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Intuitively, this is because it is believed that all physical phenomena, including the operation of classical computers, can be described using quantum mechanics, which underlies the operation of quantum computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] Conversely, any problem solvable by a quantum computer is also solvable by a classical computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] It is possible to simulate both quantum and classical computers manually with just some paper and a pen, if given enough time.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] More formally, any quantum computer can be simulated by a Turing machine.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] In other words, quantum computers provide no additional power over classical computers in terms of computability.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] This means that quantum computers cannot solve undecidable problems like the halting problem, and the existence of quantum computers does not disprove the Church–Turing thesis.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] While quantum computers cannot solve any problems that classical computers cannot already solve, it is suspected that they can solve certain problems faster than classical computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] For instance, it is known that quantum computers can efficiently factor integers, while this is not believed to be the case for classical computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The class of problems that can be efficiently solved by a quantum computer with bounded error is called BQP, for "bounded error, quantum, polynomial time".
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] More formally, BQP is the class of problems that can be solved by a polynomial-time quantum Turing machine with an error probability of at most 1/3.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] As a class of probabilistic problems, BQP is the quantum counterpart to BPP ("bounded error, probabilistic, polynomial time"), the class of problems that can be solved by polynomial-time probabilistic Turing machines with bounded error.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] It is known that ${\mathsf {BPP\subseteq BQP}}$ but there is no proof ${\mathsf {BQP\neq BPP}}$ , which intuitively would mean that quantum computers are more powerful than classical computers in terms of time complexity.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] The exact relationship of BQP to P, NP, and PSPACE is not known.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] It is further suspected that BQP is a strict superset of P, meaning that there exist problems that are efficiently solvable by quantum computers that are not efficiently solvable by deterministic classical computers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] For instance, integer factorization and the discrete logarithm problem are known to be in BQP and are suspected to be outside of P.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] On the relationship of BQP to NP, little is known beyond the fact that some NP problems that are believed not to be in P are also in BQP (integer factorization and the discrete logarithm problem are both in NP, for example).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] It is suspected that ${\mathsf {NP\nsubseteq BQP}}$ ; that is, it is believed that there are efficiently checkable problems that are not efficiently solvable by a quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/quantum-computing-p02] As a direct consequence of this belief, it is also suspected that BQP is disjoint from the class of NP-complete problems (if an NP-complete problem were in BQP, then it would follow from NP-hardness that all problems in NP are in BQP).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Shor proposed multiple similar algorithms for solving the factoring problem, the discrete logarithm problem, and the period-finding problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] "Shor's algorithm" usually refers to the factoring algorithm, but may refer to any of the three algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The discrete logarithm algorithm and the factoring algorithm are instances of the period-finding algorithm, and all three are instances of the hidden subgroup problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] On a quantum computer, to factor an integer N , Shor's algorithm runs in polynomial time, meaning the time taken is polynomial in $\log N$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Shor's algorithm is asymptotically faster than the most scalable classical factoring algorithm, the general number field sieve, which works in sub-exponential time: $O\!\left(e^{1.9(\log N)^{1/3}(\log \log N)^{2/3}}\right)$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] RSA can be broken if factoring large integers is computationally feasible.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] As far as is known, this is not possible using classical (non-quantum) computers; no classical algorithm is known that can factor integers in polynomial time.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] However, Shor's algorithm shows that factoring integers can be done with a polynomial complexity circuit on an ideal quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Thus, it might be feasible to defeat RSA by constructing a large enough quantum computer.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] This was a powerful motivator for the design and construction of quantum computers, and for the study of new quantum-computer algorithms.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] It has also facilitated research on new cryptosystems that are secure from quantum computers, collectively called post-quantum cryptography (PQC).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] As of 2026, the high error rates of quantum computers and limited number of physical qubits available for quantum error correction, laboratory demonstrations of Shor's algorithm obtain correct results in only a fraction of attempts, and have only succeeded with small semiprimes.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] In 2001, Shor's algorithm was demonstrated by a group at IBM, who factored $15$ into $3\times 5$ , using an NMR implementation of a quantum computer with seven qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] After IBM's implementation, two independent groups implemented Shor's algorithm using photonic qubits, emphasizing that multi-qubit entanglement was observed when running Shor's algorithm circuits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] In 2012, the factorization of $15$ was performed with solid-state qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Later, in 2012, the factorization of $21$ was achieved.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] In 2016, the factorization of $15$ was performed again using trapped-ion qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] However, none of these demonstrations fulfill the requirements of Shor’s algorithm: they compile the circuit using prior knowledge of the solution, and some have even oversimplified the algorithm in a way that makes it equivalent to coin flipping.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The problem that we are trying to solve is: *given an odd composite number N , find its integer factors*.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] A quantum algorithm to solve the order-finding problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] A complete factoring algorithm is possible if we're able to efficiently factor arbitrary N into just two integers p and q greater than 1, since if either p or q are not prime, then the factoring algorithm can in turn be run on those until only primes remain.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] A basic observation is that, using Euclid's algorithm, we can always compute the GCD between two integers efficiently.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] In particular, this means we can check efficiently whether N is even, in which case 2 is trivially a factor.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Let us thus assume that N is odd for the remainder of this discussion.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Afterwards, we can use efficient classical algorithms to check whether N is a prime power.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] For prime powers, efficient classical factorization algorithms exist, hence the rest of the quantum algorithm may assume that N is not a prime power.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] If those easy cases do not produce a nontrivial factor of N , the algorithm proceeds to handle the remaining case.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] We pick a random integer $2\leq a<N{.}$ A possible nontrivial divisor of N can be found by computing $\gcd(a,N)$ , which can be done classically and efficiently using the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] If this produces a nontrivial factor (meaning $\gcd(a,N)\neq 1$ ), the algorithm is finished, and the other nontrivial factor is $N/\gcd(a,N)$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] If a nontrivial factor was not identified, then this means that N and the choice of a are coprime, so a is contained in the multiplicative group of integers modulo N , having a multiplicative inverse modulo N .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] and r is the smallest positive integer satisfying this congruence.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] It can be seen from the congruence that N divides $a^{r}-1$ , written $N\mid a^{r}-1$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] This can be factored using difference of squares: $N\mid (a^{r/2}-1)(a^{r/2}+1).$ Since we have factored the expression in this way, the algorithm doesn't work for odd r (because $a^{r/2}$ must be an integer), meaning that the algorithm would have to restart with a new a .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Hereafter we can therefore assume that r is even.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] It cannot be the case that $N\mid a^{r/2}-1$ , since this would imply $a^{r/2}\equiv 1{\bmod {N}}$ , which would contradictorily imply that $r/2$ would be the order of a , which was already r .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] At this point, it may or may not be the case that $N\mid a^{r/2}+1$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] If N does not divide $a^{r/2}+1$ , then this means that we are able to find a nontrivial factor of N .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] We compute $d=\gcd(N,a^{r/2}-1).$ If $d=1$ , then $N\mid a^{r/2}+1$ was true, and a nontrivial factor of N cannot be achieved from a , and the algorithm must restart with a new a .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Otherwise, we have found a nontrivial factor of N , with the other being $N/d$ , and the algorithm is finished.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] For this step, it is also equivalent to compute $\gcd(N,a^{r/2}+1)$ ; it will produce a nontrivial factor if $\gcd(N,a^{r/2}-1)$ is nontrivial, and will not if it's trivial (where $N\mid a^{r/2}+1$ ).
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The algorithm restated shortly follows: let N be odd, and not a prime power.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] We want to output two nontrivial factors of N .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Compute $K=\gcd(a,N)$ , the greatest common divisor of a and N .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] If $K\neq 1$ , then K is a nontrivial factor of N , with the other factor being $N/K$ , and we are done.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Otherwise, use the quantum subroutine to find the order r of a .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] If g is nontrivial, the other factor is $N/g$ , and we're done.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] It has been shown that this will be likely to succeed after a few runs.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] In practice, a single call to the quantum order-finding subroutine is enough to completely factor N with very high probability of success if one uses a more advanced reduction.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The goal of the quantum subroutine of Shor's algorithm is, given coprime integers N and $1<a<N$ , to find the order r of a modulo N , the smallest positive integer r such that $a^{r}\equiv 1{\pmod {N}}$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] To achieve this, Shor's algorithm uses a quantum circuit involving two registers.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The second register uses n qubits, where n is the smallest integer such that $N\leq 2^{n}$ , i.e., $n=\left\lceil {\log _{2}N}\right\rceil$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The size of the first register determines how accurate of an approximation the circuit produces.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] It can be shown that using $2n$ qubits gives sufficient accuracy to find r .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The exact quantum circuit depends on the parameters a and N , which define the problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The following description of the algorithm uses bra–ket notation to denote quantum states, and $\otimes$ to denote the tensor product.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Use the continued fractions algorithm to extract the period r from the measurement outcomes obtained in the previous stage.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] This is a procedure to post-process (with a classical computer) the measurement data obtained from measuring the output quantum states, and retrieve the period.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The connection with quantum phase estimation was not discussed in the original formulation of Shor's algorithm, but was later proposed by Alexei Kitaev.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] In other words, it sends each eigenstate $|\psi _{j}\rangle$ of U to a state containing information close to the associated eigenvalue.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Implementing the circuit for quantum phase estimation with U requires being able to efficiently implement the gates $U^{2^{j}}$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] This can be accomplished via modular exponentiation, which is the slowest part of the algorithm.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The gate thus defined satisfies $U^{r}=I$ , which immediately implies that its eigenvalues are the r -th roots of unity $\omega _{r}^{k}=e^{2\pi ik/r}$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Using quantum phase estimation on an input state $|0\rangle ^{\otimes 2n}|\psi _{j}\rangle$ would then return the integer $2^{2n}j/r$ with high probability.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] This probability can be made arbitrarily close to 1 using extra qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Then, we apply the continued-fraction algorithm to find integers b and c , where $b/c$ gives the best fraction approximation for the approximation measured from the circuit, for $b,c<N$ and coprime b and c .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] However, while b and c are coprime, it may be the case that j and r are not coprime.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Because of that, b and c may have lost some factors that were in j and r .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] This can be remedied by rerunning the quantum order-finding subroutine an arbitrary number of times, to produce a list of fraction approximations ${\frac {b_{1}}{c_{1}}},{\frac {b_{2}}{c_{2}}},\ldots ,{\frac {b_{s}}{c_{s}}},$ where s is the number of times the subroutine was run.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Each $c_{k}$ will have different factors taken out of it because the circuit will (likely) have measured multiple different possible values of j .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] To recover the actual r value, we can take the least common multiple of each $c_{k}$ : $\operatorname {lcm} (c_{1},c_{2},\ldots ,c_{s}).$ The least common multiple will be the order r of the original integer a with high probability.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] In practice, a single run of the quantum order-finding subroutine is in general enough if more advanced post-processing is used.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Each $|\phi _{j}\rangle$ before measurement in Shor's algorithm represents a superposition of integers approximating $2^{2n}j/r$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Let $|k\rangle$ represent the most optimal integer in $|\phi _{j}\rangle$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] As k is the optimal bitstring from phase estimation, $k/2^{2{n}}$ is accurate to $j/r$ by $2n$ bits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The runtime bottleneck of Shor's algorithm is quantum modular exponentiation, which is by far slower than the quantum Fourier transform and classical pre-/post-processing.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] There are several approaches to constructing and optimizing circuits for modular exponentiation.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The simplest and (currently) most practical approach is to mimic conventional arithmetic circuits with reversible gates, starting with ripple-carry adders.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Knowing the base and the modulus of exponentiation facilitates further optimizations.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Reversible circuits typically use on the order of $n^{3}$ gates for n qubits.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Alternative techniques asymptotically improve gate counts by using quantum Fourier transforms, but are not competitive with fewer than 600 qubits owing to high constants.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Shor's algorithms for the discrete log and the order finding problems are instances of an algorithm solving the period finding problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] All three are instances of the hidden subgroup problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Given a group G with order p and generator $g\in G$ , suppose we know that $x=g^{r}\in G$ , for some $r\in \mathbb {Z} _{p}$ , and we wish to compute r , which is the discrete logarithm: $r={\log _{g}}(x)$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] Consider the abelian group $\mathbb {Z} _{p}\times \mathbb {Z} _{p}$ , where each factor corresponds to modular addition of values.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] This gives us an abelian hidden subgroup problem, where f corresponds to a group homomorphism.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The kernel corresponds to the multiples of $(r,1)$ .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] So, if we can find the kernel, we can find r .
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] A quantum algorithm for solving this problem exists.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] This algorithm is, like the factor-finding algorithm, due to Peter Shor and both are implemented by creating a superposition through using Hadamard gates, followed by implementing f as a quantum transform, followed finally by a quantum Fourier transform.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] The order-finding problem can also be viewed as a hidden subgroup problem.
[src:post-quantum-cryptography/shor-s-algorithm] For any finite abelian group G , a quantum algorithm exists for solving the hidden subgroup for G in polynomial time.
